<p>Harvard University’s Office of Career Services (OCS) is a comprehensive center serving students, faculty, administrators and alumni/ae within the Faculty of Arts and Sciences.  OCS offers a wide variety of programs, services and resources, including a Dossier Service that handles the collection, storage, and distribution of letters of recommendation and other credentials critical to the application for academic positions.  Computer support for this service was limited to a FileMaker database used to track a relatively small amount of data about dossier requests and payments. Students, graduates, and faculty had no online access to Dossier resources. The original workflow of the office included a labor intensive, paper based process.  The need for accuracy and timeliness was great, and the workload became extremely high during the few months when graduate students typically apply for academic positions.

<p><font class="sectionTitleText">Requirements</font>

<p>Harvard OCS engaged Nevo to:
<ul class="listText"><li>Redesign the Dossier Management process to streamline the dossier production effort, reduce the file space that filled an entire large room with wall-to-wall file cabinets, significantly reduce the turnaround time for dossier production and mailing, and to give the Faculty of Arts and Sciences (FAS) greater control over the creation and distribution of their personal dossiers
</li><li>Create a software solution that would be easy to manage, user friendly, and would reduce the administrative effort needed to track dossier materials so that more time could be spent advising graduate students on making good choices in their applications for academic positions
</li><li>Create the means for FAS graduate students and faculty to manage more effectively their dossier materials, and to reduce the large number of phone calls requesting information on whether a letter of reference had arrived at OCS yet
</li><li>Enable easy administration and the periodic measurement of the success of the program
</li></ul>

<p><font class="sectionTitleText">Nevo's Solution</font>

<p>Nevo first redesigned Harvard’s dossier process to eliminate more than half the steps involved in creating and sending a dossier, and at the same time freeing up the dossier storage room by creating a database of scanned copies of original letters and an offsite archive strategy that simplified and eliminated most of the need to handle original letters of recommendation in the course of day to day business.

<p>Nevo designed a self-service web-based solution for use by Harvard’s graduate students and faculty, enabling them to specify and request dossiers 24x7, with the expectation that their completed dossier would be in the mail to its destination the same or the following day, reducing a 3-5 day turnaround time to less than 24 hours. Users can track the arrival of their letters of recommendation online, and can readily manage their own information independently, on their own schedule.

<p>Nevo further developed a powerful administrative interface that enables the director of the dossier service to assist students and faculty in the use of the system, to perform a wide variety of system administration tasks, and to periodically measure the success of the program using a flexible query and reporting system.

<p>Architecturally, the OCS Dossier System is a multi-tiered Java-based web application, utilizing an XML/XSLT-based presentation layer. The print component is a Windows Service that detects when dossiers are available for printing, composes the dossiers into a composite PDF file, and adds them to a printer queue. We implemented over an Oracle database, and recommended a high-speed scanner / printer from Xerox for production of the high volume of dossiers that occurs seasonally.

<p>The system was delivered on time and on budget, has been in production since June 2002 and is currently in use by Harvard graduate students, faculty, and OCS.  As a result of the close collaboration between Nevo and Harvard’s Office of Career Services, feedback on the new Dossier System has been extremely positive.  The OCS workload is dramatically reduced, the quality of the printed dossiers is improved, clients of the system are very happy to be in control of their own dossiers, and the large dossier file room has been allocated to other uses.
